title: For Sale:  Awesome penna/kentucky rifle
postcontent: This is a gorgeous Kentucky or Pennsylvania flintlock rifle. It is contemporary, likely made in the 1960's made in old handmade style cannot tell from an 1820 original . It's top barrel flat is unsigned, but the trigger plate, behind the triggers, is stamped "N. Wendell Lancaster, O". This may have  been the builder. Research and discussions lately have also pointed possibly toward a gunsmith named Don Davison from Gray, TN. (the engravings on this rifle are incredibly similar in design (flower and feathers on the trigger guard) and execution to another gun in a local collection that is signed on the barrel by D. Davison) Mr. Davison was taught to engrave by a gentleman named Lester Smith. Of interest, Lester Smith worked with the great Hacker Martin. If you find and study the engravings of some of the magnificent Hacker Martin rifles, you can see the influence in this rifle! Just incredible! The carving and engraving work is beautiful. Incorporating german silver inlays with brass and iron. This is just a fantastic early contemporary rifle. Fine, early 42" GR Douglas Barrel in 45 caliber. 57" overall. Large german silver eagle on buttstock. All inlays engraved. Engraved trigger guard. Hidden pivot patchbox release in toe plate. My pictures don't do it justice. People who have handled it just go on and on about it! Very nice Kentucky/Pennsylvania flintlock attributed possibly to Wendell or Davison! Thanks for looking!  Price: $5895-OBO--quality part trades considered--guns, ATV ?/CIVIL WAR SWORDS/BOWIES ??

title: For Sale:  New Arrivals At bmhistorical.com. Kriegsmarine "U-Boat Flag", French MAS 1873 Service Revolver, Original Inert Type 91 Japanese Grenade
location: North Carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent:
WWII Kriegsmarine U-boat” flag in very good condition with visible Ink Kriegsmarine Eagle M Swastika, and “Reichskriegs-Flg. 0.8 x 1.35”. The flag size is 80cm by 135cm, or 30 inches by 50 inches. According to the Flaggenbuch, printed for the Oberkommando der Kriegsmarine, the flags that were designated 80cm x 135cm were for U-boats, E-boats, and Tugs. While we can’t say for certain this was on a U-boat, we can say definitively according to the German’s own reference manual that this is the size they used.
This flag has its original sewn in halyard rope in great condition. It has three minor moth holes, and one minor rip about 3 inches in size, please refer to the pictures above. There is some discoloration to the white areas of the flag, but the original red, white and black colors are still rich. This flag size is perfect to display, and would look great in any German WWII collection.

$550.00

An “excellent” example of a French MAS 1873 or St. Etienne Model 1873 Chamelot-Delvigne Double Action Service Revolver produced by Manufacture d’armes de Saint- Etienne from 1873 to 1887. Utilizing 11mm caliber ammunition, these large robust double action revolvers were used widely in World War I and used by French Resistance fighters all the way till the end of WWII. On a interesting note, this is the type of firearm used by Brandon Frasier’s character in the popular movie “The Mummy”

 All external parts are matching, even the screws. The internals also match to their own serialization. The pistol is in as found condition with a light patina on the metal surface absent of any rust or pitting. The lettering and proof marks are very crisp and clear throughout the revolver. The checkered wood grips are in good condition having just two small bruises in them, which appear to be from legitimate use. This particular revolver is dated “1878” and is in overall NRA Antique Firearm Condition of “excellent” with sharp lettering, solid checkered wood grips, and a good bore.

Antique Firearm, No FFL required and ships directly to your door!

$650.00

Original Inert WWII Japanese Type 91 Fragmentation Grenade fresh out of an estate in Charlotte, NC. This Japanese Type 91 grenade was dug from the ground, then it was demiled and made inert for souvenir and collecting purposes. The Type 91 had a seven second delay, which was impractical for a hand grenade but more suited for its other intended use as a projected munition. They could be projected from a 50mm “Knee Mortar”, rifle grenade launcher, or by hand. It mostly saw service as a hand grenade and accordingly the Japanese updated the next design, the Type 97, to have a shorter fuze time. The fuze is a percussion activated delay, started by pulling the pin and then striking the cap.

It has seen some wear on the outside, probably due to being in the ground, but appears to have the majority of the parts. This Type 91 Japanese grenade still has visible Japanese writing, and is priced modestly compared to other original WWII munitions.

$125.00

These items can also be seen on our website at: www.bmhistorical.com, along with many other antique firearms and WWI/WWII items. Remember to sign up for our newsletter!

The CW380 pistol has a 2.58 inch barrel, an overall length of 4.96 inches and a height of just 3.9 inches. It weighs just 10.2 ounces without a magazine. The pistol has a black polymer frame and features 4140 steel inserts molded into the front and back of the frame for added rigidity. It has a machined, solid 416 matte stainless steel slide and a textured polymer grip.
The Kahr CW380 features a lock breech, modified Browning type recoil lug, and utilizes Kahr's seven patents including the "safe cam" action found in all Kahr pistols. The result is a micro-compact pistol with very little recoil and quick follow-up shots. The pistol features drift adjustable white bar-dot combat rear sight and pinned-in polymer front sight.
Differences between the Kahr CW380 and Kahr P380 models include: the CW series has a conventional rifled barrel instead of the match grade polygonal barrel found on P models; the CW slide stop lever is MIM (metal-injection-molded) instead of machined; the CW series slide has fewer machining operations, and uses simple roll marking instead of engraved markings; the P380 comes with two magazines, but the CW series comes with one 6 rd steel magazine with flush baseplate. Lastly, the slide locks back after firing the last round – another feature missing on a number of other value-priced compact semi-auto pistols. The durability and reliability of the CW380 model makes it a strong consideration as a backup gun for law enforcement.

title: For Sale:  New Arrivals at BMHistorical.com! French MAS 1873 Service Revolver and Kriegsmarine "U-Boat" Flag
location: North Carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent:
An “excellent” example of a French MAS 1873 or St. Etienne Model 1873 Chamelot-Delvigne Double Action Service Revolver produced by Manufacture d’armes de Saint- Etienne from 1873 to 1887. Utilizing 11mm caliber ammunition, these large robust double action revolvers were used widely in World War I and used by French Resistance fighters all the way till the end of WWII. On a interesting note, this is the type of firearm used by Brandon Frasier’s character in the popular movie “The Mummy”

 All external parts are matching, even the screws. The internals also match to their own serialization. The pistol is in as found condition with a light patina on the metal surface absent of any rust or pitting. The lettering and proof marks are very crisp and clear throughout the revolver. The checkered wood grips are in good condition having just two small bruises in them, which appear to be from legitimate use. This particular revolver is dated “1878” and is in overall NRA Antique Firearm Condition of “excellent” with sharp lettering, solid checkered wood grips, and a good bore.

Antique Firearm, No FFL required and ships directly to your door!

$650.00

WWII Kriegsmarine U-boat” flag in very good condition with visible Ink Kriegsmarine Eagle M Swastika, and “Reichskriegs-Flg. 0.8 x 1.35”. The flag size is 80cm by 135cm, or 30 inches by 50 inches. According to the Flaggenbuch, printed for the Oberkommando der Kriegsmarine, the flags that were designated 80cm x 135cm were for U-boats, E-boats, and Tugs. While we can’t say for certain this was on a U-boat, we can say definitively according to the German’s own reference manual that this is the size they used.
This flag has its original sewn in halyard rope in great condition. It has three minor moth holes, and one minor rip about 3 inches in size, please refer to the pictures above. There is some discoloration to the white areas of the flag, but the original red, white and black colors are still rich. This flag size is perfect to display, and would look great in any German WWII collection.

$550.00
